10.body: Q31: How does ARC allocate/free memory? Answer : Allocates on heap when instance created. Tracks references. Frees when count = 0. Inserts retain/release at compile time. Q32: What do weak references do? Answer : Don't increase reference count. Automatically become nil when object deallocated. Always optional. Prevent retain cycles. Q33: What do unowned references do? Answer : Don't increase reference count. Non-optional. Assume object always exists. Crash if accessed after deallocation. Use when : Object lifetime guaranteed. Q34: Strong reference cycles in closures? Answer : Closure captures self strongly, self holds closure strongly = cycle. Fix with capture list [weak self] or [unowned self]. Q35: Capture list usage? Answer : Define how closure captures values. Syntax: { [weak self, unowned obj] in }. Prevents retain cycles. Q36: What causes memory leaks? Answer : Retain cycles, strong delegate references, closures capturing self, timers, observers not removed. Q37: Detect leaks with Instruments? Answer : Use Leaks instrument. Shows leaked objects, allocation stack trace. Also use Memory Graph Debugger in Xcode. Q38: MVVM retain cycle examples? Answer : ViewModel holds closure, closure captures ViewModel. View holds ViewModel, ViewModel holds View. Fix with weak references. Q39: Memory warning handling? Answer : iOS sends warning when low memory. Override didReceiveMemoryWarning(). Clear caches, release non-essential resources. Q40: Reference counting under the hood? Answer : Each object has reference count field. Retain increments, release decrements. When 0, dealloc called. Atomic operations for thread safety.

11.body: Q41: UIViewController lifecycle? Answer : init â†’ loadView â†’ viewDidLoad â†’ viewWillAppear â†’ viewDidAppear â†’ viewWillDisappear â†’ viewDidDisappear â†’ deinit Q42: App lifecycle? Answer : Not Running â†’ Inactive â†’ Active â†’ Background â†’ Suspended. Use SceneDelegate (iOS 13+) or AppDelegate. Q43: Frame vs bounds? Answer : Frame : Position/size in superview's coordinate system Bounds : Position/size in own coordinate system (origin usually 0,0) Q44: Auto Layout basics? Answer : Constraint-based layout system. Define relationships between views. Adapts to different screen sizes. Uses constraints (equal, greater, less). Q45: Constraints vs frames? Answer : Constraints : Adaptive, relationship-based, works across devices Frames : Fixed positions, manual calculation, breaks on rotation Q46: Table view cell reuse? Answer : Cells dequeued from reuse pool instead of creating new. Improves performance. Must reset cell state in prepareForReuse(). Q47: Diffable data source? Answer : Modern UITableView/UICollectionView data source. Uses snapshots. Automatic animations. Type-safe. No index path crashes. Q48: Compositional layout? Answer : Flexible UICollectionView layout. Compose sections with different layouts. Supports groups, items, sections. Replaces flow layout. Q49: SwiftUI view lifecycle? Answer : init â†’ body â†’ onAppear â†’ onDisappear. No viewDidLoad equivalent. Use .task for async work. Q50: @State vs @Binding? Answer : @State : Source of truth, owned by view @Binding : Two-way connection to @State, doesn't own data Q51: @ObservedObject vs @StateObject? Answer : @StateObject : Creates and owns object, survives view updates @ObservedObject : Observes external object, can be recreated Q52: Environment values? Answer : Pass data down view hierarchy without explicit parameters. System values (colorScheme) or custom. Use @Environment. Q53: NavigationStack basics? Answer : Modern navigation (iOS 16+). Programmatic navigation with path. Type-safe. Replaces NavigationView + NavigationLink. Q54: SwiftUI diff engine? Answer : Compares old and new view trees. Only updates changed views. Uses view identity and type. Efficient rendering. Q55: View identity in SwiftUI? Answer : How SwiftUI tracks views across updates. Based on type, position, and explicit id(). Affects state preservation and animations. Q56: LazyVStack and LazyHStack? Answer : Load views on-demand as they appear. Better performance for long lists. Unlike VStack/HStack which load all immediately. Q57: Scroll performance best practices? Answer : Use lazy stacks, avoid heavy computations in body, cache images, use .drawingGroup() for complex views, minimize state changes. Q58: Rendering pipeline in SwiftUI? Answer : State change â†’ body called â†’ diff â†’ update â†’ render. Three phases: update, layout, render. Optimized by SwiftUI. Q59: UIKit vs SwiftUI architecture? Answer : UIKit : Imperative, mutable, view controllers, delegates SwiftUI : Declarative, immutable, views, data flow Q60: When to mix SwiftUI + UIKit? Answer : Use UIViewRepresentable/UIViewControllerRepresentable. When: UIKit component not in SwiftUI, legacy code, specific UIKit features needed.

12.body: Q61: URLSession flow? Answer : Create URLRequest â†’ Create URLSession â†’ Create task (data/download/upload) â†’ Resume task â†’ Handle response/data â†’ Parse. Q62: DataTask vs DownloadTask? Answer : DataTask : Returns data in memory, for small responses DownloadTask : Saves to file, for large files, supports background Q63: Decoding JSON with Codable? Answer : JSONDecoder().decode(Type.self, from: data). Struct must conform to Codable. Use CodingKeys for custom mapping. Q64: Handling errors in networking? Answer : Check URLError, HTTP status codes, decoding errors. Use Result type. Provide user-friendly messages. Implement retry logic. Q65: What is HTTP caching? Answer : Store responses to avoid repeated requests. URLCache handles automatically. Control with Cache-Control headers. Improves performance. Q66: What are URLRequests? Answer : Encapsulates request details: URL, method (GET/POST), headers, body, timeout. Immutable. Use URLComponents for URL building. Q67: REST vs GraphQL? Answer : REST : Multiple endpoints, over/under-fetching, simple GraphQL : Single endpoint, request exact data, complex Q68: Handling status codes? Answer : 2xx = success, 3xx = redirect, 4xx = client error, 5xx = server error. Check httpResponse.statusCode. Handle each appropriately. Q69: Retry mechanism? Answer : Exponential backoff, max retry count, only retry on specific errors (network, 5xx). Use DispatchQueue.asyncAfter or Task.sleep. Q70: Debouncing network calls? Answer : Delay execution until user stops typing. Cancel previous requests. Use Timer, Combine's debounce, or Task cancellation.

43.body: Question : "What's the difference between value and reference types?" Your Answer : "Value types like structs are copied when assigned or passed to functions, so each variable has its own independent copy. Reference types like classes share the same instance, so multiple variables can point to the same object. This affects memory management - value types are typically stored on the stack and don't need ARC, while reference types are on the heap and use reference counting. It also impacts thread safety - value types are inherently safer because each thread gets its own copy. In Swift, structs, enums, and basic types are value types, while classes and closures are reference types." Follow-up : "When would you choose one over the other?" Your Answer : "I use structs for simple data models where I want value semantics - like Point, Size, or User data. They're safer by default and prevent accidental mutations. I use classes when I need inheritance, when modeling identity (like a User session), or when I need reference semantics - like a view controller or a shared cache. Classes are also necessary for Objective-C interop."

74.body: Question : "What's the difference between weak and unowned?" Answer : "Both weak and unowned don't increase the reference count, preventing retain cycles. The key difference is that weak is optional and automatically becomes nil when the object is deallocated, while unowned is non-optional and will crash if you try to access it after deallocation. I use weak for delegates and optional relationships where the object might not exist. I use unowned when I'm certain the object will outlive the reference, like a child object referencing its parent that owns it."

8.body: Q1: What's the difference between struct and class? Answer : Structs are value types (copied), classes are reference types (shared). Classes support inheritance and deinitializers, structs don't. Key Point : let on struct = immutable. let on class = constant reference, mutable properties. Q2: Value type vs reference type? Answer : Value types (struct, enum) are copied on assignment. Reference types (class) share the same instance. Memory : Value types on stack (usually), reference types on heap. Q3: How does ARC work? Answer : Automatic Reference Counting tracks strong references. When count reaches 0, instance is deallocated. Works at compile-time. Formula : +1 on create, -1 on remove, 0 = dealloc Q4: Strong, weak, unowned? Answer : Strong : Default, increases reference count Weak : Optional, doesn't increase count, becomes nil when deallocated Unowned : Non-optional, doesn't increase count, crashes if accessed after dealloc Q5: What causes retain cycles? Answer : Two objects holding strong references to each other. Common in: closures capturing self, parent-child relationships, delegates. Fix : Use weak or unowned to break the cycle. Q6: What are property wrappers? Answer : Reusable code that adds behavior to properties. Examples: @State, @Published, @UserDefault. Syntax : @propertyWrapper struct Wrapper { var wrappedValue: T } Q7: What is Codable? Answer : Protocol for encoding/decoding. Combines Encodable + Decodable. Auto-synthesized for simple types. Usage : struct User: Codable { let name: String } Q8: map, flatMap, compactMap? Answer : map : Transform each element flatMap : Transform + flatten nested arrays compactMap : Transform + remove nils Q9: What are generics? Answer : Write flexible, reusable code that works with any type. Provides type safety without duplication. Example : func swap<T>(_ a: inout T, _ b: inout T) Q10: What is a protocol? Answer : Blueprint of methods, properties, and requirements. Defines "what" not "how". Enables polymorphism. Key : Can be adopted by classes, structs, and enums. Q11: Protocol vs class inheritance? Answer : Protocol : Multiple adoption, no implementation (unless extension) Class : Single inheritance, provides implementation Q12: Associated types in protocols? Answer : Placeholder type in protocol, defined by conforming type. Like generics for protocols. Syntax : associatedtype Item Q13: What are extensions for? Answer : Add functionality to existing types without subclassing. Can add methods, computed properties, initializers, protocol conformance. Cannot : Add stored properties or override existing methods. Q14: Static vs class methods? Answer : static : Cannot be overridden class : Can be overridden in subclasses (classes only) Q15: What is a closure? Answer : Self-contained block of code that can be passed around. Can capture values from surrounding context. Types : Global functions, nested functions, closure expressions. Q16: Escaping vs non-escaping? Answer : Non-escaping (default): Executed before function returns Escaping (@escaping): Can outlive function, stored or called later Q17: What is @autoclosure? Answer : Automatically wraps expression in closure. Delays evaluation. Used for short-circuit evaluation. Example : func assert(_ condition: @autoclosure () -> Bool) Q18: What is inout? Answer : Pass parameter by reference, allowing function to modify original value. Creates copy-in, copy-out behavior. Syntax : func increment(_ value: inout Int) Q19: What is optional chaining? Answer : Query optional properties/methods with ?. Returns nil if any part is nil. Alternative to forced unwrapping. Example : user?.address?.street Q20: Computed vs stored properties? Answer : Stored : Hold value in memory Computed : Calculate value on access, no storage

9.body: Q21: What is GCD? Answer : Grand Central Dispatch - low-level API for managing concurrent operations. Uses queues to execute tasks. Key : Abstracts thread management. Q22: Sync vs async? Answer : Sync : Blocks until task completes Async : Returns immediately, task runs in background Q23: Serial vs concurrent queues? Answer : Serial : One task at a time, in order Concurrent : Multiple tasks simultaneously Q24: What is a race condition? Answer : Multiple threads access shared data simultaneously, causing unpredictable results. Fixed with synchronization (locks, queues, actors). Q25: What is a deadlock? Answer : Two or more threads waiting for each other, causing permanent block. Often from nested sync calls on same queue. Q26: How does DispatchGroup work? Answer : Groups multiple tasks, notifies when all complete. Use enter()/leave() or pass to async calls. Usage : Coordinate multiple network calls. Q27: What is OperationQueue? Answer : Higher-level abstraction over GCD. Supports dependencies, cancellation, priorities. Uses Operation objects. Q28: How does async-await work? Answer : Modern concurrency syntax. async marks function as asynchronous, await suspends until result ready. Compiler handles continuations. Q29: What are actors? Answer : Reference type that protects mutable state from data races. Only one task can access at a time. Automatic synchronization. Q30: What does MainActor do? Answer : Global actor representing main thread. Ensures UI updates happen on main thread. Use @MainActor annotation.
